abstract: His exit comes just months after he won a third Senate term in Ohio, raising hopes among some Democrats that he was the party’s best bet for winning back the Midwest.
snippet: His exit comes just months after he won a third Senate term in Ohio, raising hopes among some Democrats that he was the party’s best bet for winning back the Midwest.
lead_paragraph: Senator Sherrod Brown, the populist Ohio Democrat known for extolling the “dignity of work,” announced Thursday that he would not seek the Democratic nomination for president, ceding the primary field to other left-leaning candidates with broader national appeal.

abstract: The former secretary of state told a New York television station that she would continue to speak out on issues, saying, “I’m not going anywhere.”
snippet: The former secretary of state told a New York television station that she would continue to speak out on issues, saying, “I’m not going anywhere.”
lead_paragraph: Hillary Clinton, the former secretary of state and first lady who lost the White House to Donald J. Trump in 2016, said officially on Monday what has been unofficially clear for months: She is not running for president again in 2020.

headline_main: Hillary Clinton Says She Is Not Running for President in 2020
headline_print_headline: Clinton Says She Will Not Be Running Again

abstract: Senator Chuck Schumer says Senate Democrats plan daily floor speeches on climate change, a special select committee and climate legislation to run on next year — and enact in 2021.
snippet: Senator Chuck Schumer says Senate Democrats plan daily floor speeches on climate change, a special select committee and climate legislation to run on next year — and enact in 2021.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Facing a showdown vote as early as this month over the embattled “Green New Deal,” Senate Democrats are preparing a counteroffensive to make combating climate change a central issue of their 2020 campaigns — a striking shift on an issue they have shied away from for the past decade.

headline_main: Pressed by Climate Activists, Senate Democrats Plan to ‘Go on Offense’
headline_print_headline: In Bid for Millennials, Senate Democrats Plan To Emphasize Climate
byline_original: By Coral Davenport and Sheryl Gay Stolberg

abstract: They can appeal to moderate voters without betraying progressive values.
snippet: They can appeal to moderate voters without betraying progressive values.
lead_paragraph: The energy in the 2020 Democratic campaign has been coming from the left. Candidates are pushing Medicare for All, a Green New Deal, a wealth tax and other ideas that are more progressive than anything a recent Democratic nominee has favored.

headline_main: A Dose of Moderation Would Help Democrats
headline_print_headline: A Dose of  Moderation  For Democrats

abstract: Democrats won big in the 2018 midterm elections in Pennsylvania, but some wonder if they can win back the state from President Trump if the party veers too far left in 2020.
snippet: Democrats won big in the 2018 midterm elections in Pennsylvania, but some wonder if they can win back the state from President Trump if the party veers too far left in 2020.
lead_paragraph: SHALER, Pa. — This should be an upbeat moment for Pennsylvania Democrats, desperate to deprive President Trump of a second term.

headline_main: Pennsylvania Democrats Wonder How Far Is Too Far Left in 2020
headline_print_headline: In Pennsylvania, Skewing Left May Sap Momentum of 2018

abstract: Mr. Inslee has made climate change and the environment his signature issues, though he has had mixed success in getting some ideas put into practice in his home state.
snippet: Mr. Inslee has made climate change and the environment his signature issues, though he has had mixed success in getting some ideas put into practice in his home state.
lead_paragraph: SEATTLE — Jay Inslee, the governor of Washington and former member of Congress who has made climate change and the environment his signature issues, jumped into the crowded field of 2020 Democratic contenders for president on Friday.

headline_main: Can a Horrible Boss Be a Great Leader?

abstract: Managers who aggressively “demand” excellence from their employees won’t necessarily produce it, researchers say.
snippet: Managers who aggressively “demand” excellence from their employees won’t necessarily produce it, researchers say.
lead_paragraph: Senator Amy Klobuchar’s nascent campaign is fending off a stream of stories from former staffers that she was a volatile, highhanded boss who often demeaned and humiliated people who worked for her. She has one of the highest rates of turnover in the Senate.
